How big could a sardine grow, if it weren't caught and canned? Not very. When sardines get bigger they become pilchards, which are a favoured food of marlin, humpbacks, minkes, seals, dolphins, cormorants, gulls and sharks. Plus they make a great bait for tailor. The shelf life of a can of sardines far exceeds the expected life of a sardine in the ocean. David Gribble, New Lambton Is it an African sardine or a European sardine? Josh Quigley, Gerringong A sardine can refer to any one of several small species of herring that belong to the Clupeidae family. The Australian pilchard or sardine is the same species found off California, Peru, South Africa, Chile and Japan, and is closely related to the European sardine (Sardina pilchardus). This species can live up to nine years and reach 26cm at maturity. The largest sardine is the Atlantic sardine or Atlantic menhaden (Brevoortia tyrannus), which can grow up to 40cm at maturity. Sam Hunter, Wentworth Falls Is there an easy, environmentally friendly way to reduce the bulk of polystyrene packing so we can fit it in the rubbish bin? Once upon a time, precious items were packaged in polystyrene balls, but nowadays these are made from potato. Wet them and they shrivel to nothing. I can't imagine why larger pieces of packaging are not made from this clever and environmentally friendly medium. Josephine Howie, Mosman If the proof of the pudding is in the eating, why is it wrong to have your cake and eat it? Probably for the same reason that many hands make light work but too many cooks spoil the broth. Tony Alston, West Haven Because that's the way the cookie crumbles. Mary Carde, Cherrybrook The proof of the pudding is in the eating - that is, a pudding's looks are not important, the taste is. But it isn't "wrong" to have your cake and eat it; the aphorism is "You can't have your cake and eat it too", meaning you can't be the proud owner of a non-renewable resource as well as using it up. A bit like Warragamba Dam. Ros Keifer, South West Rocks What happens if you eat the silica from those "do not eat" packets? Packets of silica are placed in the packaging of consumer electronics and other products. This provides some protection from damp and condensation during shipping or storage. The silica tends to absorb the moisture before it damages the fragile item. If you eat the silica, your package is more likely to be damaged by moisture. David A. Vincent, Lidcombe The hospital people will think you're a moron. Laura Perusco, Gerringong Nothing much, but it won't taste like either pudding or cake. J. Barrie Brown, Gordon Why do footballers run and remove their shirts when they score goals? So they can score off the field as well. Randolph Magri-Overend, Point Clare To show that they have hair on their chest - and in women's teams, that they have not. Gerry Wagemans, Epping To cool and display their hot and sweaty pectorals. Erhard Gohl, Allambie Heights Testosterone. Peter Dresser, Coonamble I don't know, but I do wonder why women's football isn't a more popular spectator sport. Laura Perusco, Gerringong To show sportswomen how to celebrate after a win. George Hayes, Sydney What do you want them to do? Stand stock still and remove their shorts? John Edwards, Dulwich Hill They ask quesions, people submit answers.

I think it's about time that I expressed my <big>extreme disdain</big> for bad/non-existent grammar. Most people know about it, but I feel the need to point it out when BUSINESSES are putting out advertisements that BLATANTLY IGNORE the rules of grammar. And that it's pretty much accepted.

Okay, I understand that some rules of grammar are hard to remember (the apostrophe of possession, for example), but one particular card completely lost it on one of the most simple there is - "your/you're". What's worse is that it's not uncommon. Grammar is a lost art.

Lack of grammar in general shits me, but when businesses can advertise without it being correct... that's just too much.

Onion frying in butter.... is there a better smell? Probably, but this is bloody good. I'm back on the blood capsules (ugh), but they should make me feel better/actually awake. I shouldn't have stopped taking them so early, really, but... oh well. I think i'm in a vicious cycle. I realised that it was around this time last year that I was sick/getting sick (I think). I should see a doctor, rather than just sitting here and whinging about it, but there are just so many symptoms, and I figure i've already diagnosed myself anyway (with various cancers and such). So we'll see. Enough about that though. Onto something far more enjoyable - pumpkin soup. There is some in the making here, and it's looking and smelling delicious. mmmmmmmmmmmmmmmm. I love chicken stock. I reckon I could drink a glass of it. We also have prawns, avocado, pineapple and marinated fetta. I sure do love it when mum goes shopping. All this talk of food has got me hungry, so i'm going to go enjoy this glorious food. May all have good ones and buckets of gold. EDIT: I keep looking at the clock at 11:37 (hence the avatar). Every night (and day), without fail, I look at the clock at that time. It's starting to freak me out. It's been happening for a while now. Does anyone know anything about numerology? I want to know what it means.

... How can a shampoo be fast acting? Are other shampoos slow acting? Who am I? What am I doing with my life?

No, I don't really expect anyone to know what the shampoo is on about (or me, for that matter), I just thought it odd.



That is all.
